===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|ang}} {{term|swat|swāt|lang=ang}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{recons|swait-|lang=gem-pro}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{recons|swoyd-||to sweat|lang=ine-pro}}, {{recons|sweyd-|lang=ine-pro}}. Cognate with West Frisian {{term|swit|lang=fy}}, Dutch {{term|zweet|lang=nl}}, German {{term|Schweiß|lang=de}}, Danish {{term|sved|lang=da}}, Swedish {{term|svett|lang=sv}}, Yiddish {{term|שוויצן|sc=Hebr|tr=shvitsn|lang=yi}} (English {{term|shvitz|lang=en}}), French {{term|sueur|lang=fr}}, Persian {{term|sc=fa-Arab|خوی|tr=xway|lang=fa}}, Sanskrit {{term|स्वेद|tr=svéda|lang=sa|sc=Deva}}, Latvian {{term|sviedri|lang=lt}}, Tocharian B {{term|syā-|lang=txb}}, and Albanian {{term|djersë|lang=sq}}.

====Noun====
{{en-noun|-}}

# [[fluid|Fluid]] that exits the [[body]] through [[pore]]s in the [[skin]] usually due to [[physical]] [[stress]] and/or [[high]] [[temperature]] for the purpose of regulating body temperature and removing certain compounds from the [[circulation]].
# {{British|slang|military slang|especially WWI}} A [[soldier]] (especially one who is old or experienced).<!-- cf. http://www.thefreedictionary.com/sweat and sources at [[old sweat]] -->
# {{historical}} The [[sweating sickness]].
#* '''2009''', Hilary Mantel, ''Wolf Hall'', Fourth Estate 2010, p. 131:
#*: When the '''sweat''' comes back this summer, 1528, people say, as they did last year, that you won't get it if you don't think about it.

